## 📂 Project Structure

<CodeBlock language="text" content="zihntech-landing-page/
├── 📁 Asset/
│   ├── 🖼️ Image/
│   ├── 🎬 Video/
│   └── 📄 Readme.md
├── 🌐 index.html
├── 🎨 style.css
├── ⚡ script.js
└── 📘 README.md"/>

This structure was intentionally organized to help me practice how professional frontend projects separate **assets, styles, scripts, and documentation**.

---

## 🧠 What I Learned

Building this project taught me lessons that go beyond syntax.

### Frontend Skills

* Creating semantic HTML layouts
* Designing responsive interfaces with CSS
* Linking stylesheets and JavaScript files correctly
* Structuring folders for scalability

### Developer Skills

* Using Git for version control
* Creating meaningful commits
* Pushing code to GitHub
* Writing professional README documentation
* Debugging beginner mistakes patiently
* Understanding that confusion is part of the learning process

One of the most important lessons I learned is this:

> **Making mistakes is not evidence that you are failing; it is evidence that you are actively building something new.**

---

## 🚧 Current Status

<Badge color="success" label="Actively Improving"/>

This project is still evolving as I continue my training at **Zihntech Academy**.

### Planned Improvements

* Better mobile responsiveness
* Accessibility enhancements
* Smoother animations and transitions
* Cleaner JavaScript architecture
* Performance optimization
* More refined UI/UX design

I plan to revisit this repository regularly and update it as my skills become stronger.

---

## 🤝 A Note to Developers Reviewing This Repository

If you are a **junior developer**, I hope this project reminds you that your first repository does not need to be perfect to be valuable.

The hardest part is often not writing code — it is having the courage to publish your work.

If you are a **senior developer**, I would genuinely appreciate constructive feedback on:

* 🧹 Code structure
* 🏷️ Naming conventions
* 📱 Responsiveness
* ♿ Accessibility
* ⚡ Performance
* 📐 Beginner-friendly best practices

I am not trying to appear experienced; I am trying to **become experienced through consistent practice, honest learning, and continuous improvement**.

